         <abstract>
            <p>We cannot rely on the market mechanism to tell businessmen what society wants in the way of standards of responsibility. It is preposterous to assert that we have pollution, drug addition, traffic congestion and slum tenements because we want them. Furthermore, the professional investor who does not begin to investigate corporate practice relating to these problems runs the risk of encouraging corporate investment that may subsequently be obsoleted by new laws enforcing higher standards.</p>
